<Layout
  title="Gopher vs Mole: How To Tell Which One Is Destroying Your Yard | How To Kill Gophers"
  description="Crescent mound with a plugged hole? Gopher. Volcano mound with a center hole? Mole. Learn how to tell them apart and why it matters for treatment."
  schemas={[articleSchema]}
>
  <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <a href="/">Home</a> › Gopher vs Mole
  </nav>

  <header>
    <h1>Gopher vs Mole</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">How To Tell Which One Is Destroying Your Yard</p>
  </header>

  <main>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
      <p>Look at the mound. If it's a <strong>crescent or fan shape</strong> with a plugged hole off to one side, you have a gopher. If it's a <strong>symmetrical volcano shape</strong> with a hole dead center, you have a mole. Get the ID right first — gopher traps don't catch moles, and mole traps don't catch gophers. Treating the wrong animal wastes time and money.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Side-by-Side Comparison</h2>
      <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
        <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.95rem;">
          <thead>
            <tr style="background: #f4f4f5;">
              <th style="text-align: left; padding: 0.6rem 1rem; border-bottom: 2px solid #e4e4e7;"></th>
              <th style="text-align: left; padding: 0.6rem 1rem; border-bottom: 2px solid #e4e4e7; color: #b91c1c;">Gopher</th>
              <th style="text-align: left; padding: 0.6rem 1rem; border-bottom: 2px solid #e4e4e7; color: #1d4ed8;">Mole</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {[
              ["Mound shape", "Crescent or fan, plugged hole off to the side", "Symmetrical volcano, hole dead center"],
              ["Diet", "Roots, bulbs, tubers — pure herbivore", "Grubs, worms, insects — never eats plants"],
              ["Tunnel depth", "6–18 inches, deep main runs", "2–5 inches, shallow surface ridges"],
              ["Plant damage", "Yes — pulls plants down from below", "Rarely — lifts turf but doesn't eat roots"],
              ["Surface ridges", "Uncommon", "Very common — raised soil trails across lawn"],
              ["Activity season", "Year-round", "Spring and fall most active"],
              ["Size", "6–8 inches, larger body", "4–7 inches, paddle-shaped front feet"],
            ].map(([label, gopher, mole], i) => (
              <tr style={i % 2 === 0 ? "background: #fafafa;" : ""}>
                <td style="padding: 0.6rem 1rem; font-weight: 600; border-bottom: 1px solid #e4e4e7;">{label}</td>
                <td style="padding: 0.6rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #e4e4e7;">{gopher}</td>
                <td style="padding: 0.6rem 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #e4e4e7;">{mole}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Why Getting the ID Right Matters</h2>
      <p>Gophers and moles cause completely different types of damage and require completely different treatment. A gopher is an herbivore — it's actively eating your plants, bulbs, and roots. A mole is an insectivore — it's hunting grubs and worms underground and the surface damage is just collateral from tunneling.</p>
      <p>If you set gopher bait in a mole tunnel, nothing happens. The mole won't touch it. If you set a surface mole trap over a deep gopher run, you'll never get a catch. Misidentification is the number one reason people spend weeks "treating" a pest problem with zero results.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>How To ID Yours — Step by Step</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Find a fresh mound</strong> — fresh means damp soil pushed up within the last 24–48 hours.</li>
        <li><strong>Check the shape.</strong> Get down and look at it from the side. Fan/crescent with a plugged hole off center = gopher. Dome/volcano with a center plug = mole.</li>
        <li><strong>Look for surface ridges.</strong> If you see raised trails of soil running across your lawn between mounds, that's a mole's shallow feeding tunnel. Gophers don't leave surface trails.</li>
        <li><strong>Check your plants.</strong> Pull up a plant near the damage zone. If the roots are chewed off or the whole plant pulls out easily with no roots attached, that's a gopher. If the roots are intact but the plant is just heaved up from below, that's mole tunneling.</li>
        <li><strong>Probe for tunnel depth.</strong> Use a rod or screwdriver. Gopher main runs are 6–18 inches down. Mole feeding tunnels are only 2–5 inches — you'll hit the void almost immediately.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="field-notes" style="background: #fdfdfd; padding: 1.5rem; border: 1px solid #ddd; border-left: 5px solid #d4af37; margin: 1.5rem 0 0; border-radius: 4px;">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #222;">The Bagger's Field Notes</h3>
        <p style="font-style: italic; color: #555;">"Nine out of ten people who tell me they have gophers actually have gophers. But the ones who are wrong are always wrong the same way — they see raised ridges in the lawn and assume gopher. That's a mole every time. Gophers work deep. If you can feel a tunnel ridge with your foot, you've got moles."</p>
      </div>
    </section>

